Predict Fuel Poverty With Less Information¶

the case of the UK in 2015

This paper explores the Fuel Poverty Dataset, part of the English Housing Survey,published by: Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy in 2015. This document presents both an exploration analysis and an comparison of popular classification algorithms to predict whether a household is in fuel poverty.

1. Introduction¶

Fuel poverty is publicly recognized as one of the biggest social-equity problems in Europe and US these years with severe consequences that include definition of quality of life, adverse effects on public health and inequity(Lyra, Mirasgedis and Tourkolias, 2022). Excess winter mortality rate is observed in old and damp households. Similarly, during hot summer, households that cant afford air-conditioner can also make the most venerable suffer.

There is, however, no single definition of fuel poverty across the Europe. The UK's definition for fuel poverty is that: people who are in fuel poverty are those whose fuel costs are above average national median level but were they spend that amount, they would be left with a residual income below official poverty line (BEIS, 2018). In France, the definition for fuel poverty is that any person who experiences specific difficulties in accessing the power supply required to satisfy their basic needs, due to inadequacy of their resources their living conditions, is in fuel poverty (Tyszler and Leseur, 2013).

Generally, fuel poverty results from a mixture of three factors: low income, higher energy prices and inadequate household energy requirements (BEIS, 2018). More recently, fuel poverty is considered as a multidimensional social problem and therefore is also related to household composition, dwelling type, household demography, health status of its residents and employment status, etc. (Mashhoodi et al.,2019). Moreover, Mashhoodi et al. (2019) suggests that geographical factor can impact the levels of fuel poverty.

This study adopts Hills.(2011) definition of fuel poverty' to explore the fuel poverty dataset in 2015 of the UK published by Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy. According to the definition, 4 types of households can be identified: 1) households with high income and low fuel costs (HILC), 2) households with high income and high fuel costs (HIHC), 3) households with low income and low fuel costs (LILC) and 4) households with low income and high fuel costs (LIHC). Only LIHC households are regarded as households in fuel poverty. The dataset has labeled household into only two types, i.e. households in fuel poverty and households not in fuel poverty.

But under actual circumstances, it's difficult to get the accurate infomation about household income and fuel costs. Collecting such data by energy companies may also violate the General Data Protection Regulation (GDRR). Additionally, people also regard this information as privacy and are sometimes reluctant to offer.

To solve the paradox, popular classification algorithms are tested using dataset that removes fuel costs (fuel_costs), household income('hh_income') and household costs( HousingCosts). By doing so, we want to test if only using the basic information such as incomde deciles, geographic information, EPC rating, household demographic, and dwelling characteristic we can still have a reseasonable prediction of fuel poverty. The algorithms tested include Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Random Forest, Multi-layer Perceptron (MLP) classifier, and Adaboost Classifier.

The study tries to answer the following questions:

Q1. Which classification method have the best performance for fuel poverty prediction?

Q2. Which fatcors are most related to fuel poverty?

2.Literature review¶

Literature
According to Fazanie and Kahouli.(2019), the methods to measuring fuel poverty can be categorized into 3 general groups: (a) objective approaches is based on the proportion of household income required to keep the living space comfortable, (b) subjective evalution based on the level of avalible energy equipments or appliances, and composite indicators that considering multiple factors such as household characteristics, employment status, health conditions of residents, etc.

The most widely applied objective approaches for measuring fuel poverty is the 'energy expenditure'. Generally, the threshold of 10% of household income on energy bills is often used to recognize whether a hous is in fuel poverty or not. The famous LIHC approach is introduced by Hills (2012) that fuel poor households have both a low income and high energy consumption. Another variant of the approach is the After-Fuel-Costs Poverty (AFCP) proposed by Hills. (2011). Housholds whose net income after paying energy bills is lower than 60% of the median household's net income. England adopts an approach that takes into account the Energy Performance Certifcate (EPC) rating.The EPC rating represents level of the energy efficiency of dwellings with A the highest and F the lowest. Only LIHC households whose EPC rating is D are labeled as fuel poor households.

Households in fuel poverty are mainly associated with low income and high energy expenditures. Therefore, these two factors are furthur related to high energy prices, poor housing, inefficient heating or cooling equipments, geographic factors, number and age structure of residents, and emloyment status.

2 Logistic regression models have been employed to link fuel poverty to sevral of the above-mentioned factors in a study of fuel poverty of Greece(Lyra, Mirasgedis and Tourkolias, 2022). They suggests that types of dwelling, location of households, education level of main bread-earner of the housesholds are the main factors contributes to fuel poverty in Greece.

3.0 | Methodology¶

Data characteristics
There are 4 types of Independent Variables in our dataset, including expenditure variables, energy efficiency variables, and dwelling characteristics variables, household characteritics variables. The expenditure variables include household income, toatl energy costs,housing costs; the energy efficiency variables include EPC rating, central heating or not, main fuel type, wall type, insulation thickness, boiler or not; the dwelling characteristics variables includes Region, Tenure, dwelling types, age of dwelling, floor area; household characteritics variables include houshold composition, working status, ethnic origin, household size, and number of residents in sick.

Method
Supervised learning is one of the two branches of machine learning that enables the model to predict future outcomes after being trained with past data as input. Supervised learning models can be further classied into regression and classification according to the type of output. The outputs of regression model are continuous while the outputs are categorical for classification(Chandra Sen, Hajra and Ghosh, 2020). In our case, there are only two outputs of fuel poverty, namely, in fuel poverty and not in fuel poverty. Therefore, it's a classification problem.

Popular Classification algorithms include Logistic regression, decision regression, random forest, Adaboost, in which logistic regression is often used to predict binary outcomes.

Resampling
Most of the households are not in fuel poverty, so the dataset is imbalanced. In this case, both upsampling and downsampling techniques are applied before classification.

# the plot_freq function
def plot_freq(a, xlabel, title):
    # suppress warnings
    import warnings
    warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
    # plot
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    fig.set_size_inches(8, 5)
    fp_1 =fp.loc[fp["In_fuel_poverty"] == 1]   # the dataframe of households in fuel poverty
    fp_2=fp.loc[fp["In_fuel_poverty"] == 0]    # the dataframe of households not in fuel poverty
    x=list(fp[a].value_counts().to_dict().keys())
    y=list(fp[a].value_counts().to_dict().values()) # the total number of households
    y1=list(fp_1[a].value_counts().to_dict().values()) # in fuel poverty
    y2=list(fp_2[a].value_counts().to_dict().values()) # not in fuel poverty
    
    # fig 1
    ax.bar(x,y1, label="In Fuel Poverty")
    ax.bar(x,y2,bottom=y1, label="Not In Fuel Poverty")
    ax.set_xticklabels(x, rotation=90,fontsize= 12)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel,fontsize= 14,weight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel('Number of Households',fontsize= 14,weight='bold')
    ax.set_title(f'The Distribution Households of different {title}',fontsize=16, weight='bold')
    plt.legend()
    
    # fig 2
    ax2=ax.twinx()
    y3 =[i*100/j for i, j in zip(y1,y)] ## the percentage of fuel poverty  in differnt 
    plt.plot(x, y3)
    ax2.set_ylabel("% of Households in fuel poverty")
    plt.show()

# the plot_box function explore the realtionship between `hh_income` or	`fuel_costs` with other variables 
def plot_box(a,b,xlabel,ylabel):
    fig,ax = plt.subplots()
    fig.set_size_inches(8, 5)
    ax=sns.boxplot(x=fp[a],y=fp[b])
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(),fontsize=12) #,rotation=45
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel,fontsize=14,weight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel,fontsize=14,weight='bold')
    ax.set_title(f'{ylabel} of different {xlabel}',fontsize=16,color='black',weight='bold')
    plt.show()

5. Classification Algorithms¶

As shown in Figure 1, the dataset is imbalanced, with only minority of households are in fuel poverty. However, most of the classification algorithms are designed for balanced datasets. Hence, the results of the model can have poor predictve performance for minority class while tend to be overfitting for majority class. The most common methods to mitigate this problem are downsampling and upsampling. This section will test the performance with both downsampling and upsampling techinques to compare the results. To evaluate the results, f1 score is used, which combines the precision and recall of a classifier into a single metric by taking their harmonic mean.

The re-sampling and train-test split function

In [ ]:
def sampling(sample_method):
    # data split
    X=fp_test.drop(['In_fuel_poverty'],axis=1)
    X=pd.get_dummies(X)
    y=fp_test["In_fuel_poverty"]
    
    ## chosing method
    if sample_method =="upsampling":
        from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE # oversampling method
        smote = SMOTE()
        X, y = smote.fit_resample(X, y)
        print("1. Shape of New Dataset:\n",y.value_counts())
    ## downsampling
    elif sample_method =="downsampling":
        from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler
        rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42, replacement=True) # downsampling 
        X, y = rus.fit_resample(X, y)
        print("1. Shape of New Dataset:\n",y.value_counts())
    else:
        print("1.Please Check the spelling of the sampling method, the result is for the original dataset")
        
    # print size of the size before and after resampling
    #print("Orginal dataset:\n",fp_test["In_fuel_poverty"].value_counts())
    
    
    # dictVectorizer (modified from CASA workshop 7)
    from sklearn.feature_extraction import DictVectorizer
    vec = DictVectorizer()  # create the DictVectorizer object
    data_dict = X.to_dict('records')
    vec_array = vec.fit_transform(data_dict).toarray()  # execute process on the record dictionaries and transform the result into a numpy array object
    features =vec.get_feature_names_out() 
    
    # split 
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
    random_state_split = 101
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(vec_array, y, random_state=random_state_split)
    
    #(modified from CASA workshop 7)
    X_train = np.nan_to_num(X_train) 
    X_test = np.nan_to_num(X_test)
    y_train = np.nan_to_num(y_train)
    y_test = np.nan_to_num(y_test)
    
    print("2. The size of training and testing datasets are:",len(X_train),len(X_test))

    # return 
    return X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test,features

5.2 | Functions for classification method performance¶

The classification_perform function combines the sampling function to give (1) the metrics of classifiction methods for either up or down sampling method, and (2) a plot of the feather importance.

The class_results function further simply classification_perform function to give results for a given algorithm with up and downsampling methods.

        #from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
        clf = LogisticRegression(random_state = random_state,max_iter =max_iter)
        #clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    elif algorithm == "DecisionTreeClassifier":
        #from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
        clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state = random_state)
        #clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

        #from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostClassifier
        clf = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state = random_state)
        #clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    elif algorithm == "RandomForestClassifier":
        clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = random_state)

        print("Please check the spelling of algorithm")

def class_results(algorithm):
    print("The results for Undersampling:")
    print(classification_perform(sample_method="downsampling",algorithm="algorithm"))
    print("The results for Upsampling:")
    print(classification_perform(sample_method="upsampling",algorithm="algorithm"))

6.4 | Feature importance¶

To better understand the importance of of each variable, Chi-Suqare Test is performed. Chi-Square Test is a simple tool to test if two variables are highly correlated or independent of each other. By implementing the test, we can know that which factors are highly correlated with fuel poverty.

In [ ]:
# the following method is 
def feature_importance(sample_method):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test,features=sampling(sample_method=sample_method)
    fs = SelectKBest(score_func=chi2, k='all') # SelectKBest is used to do feature selection.
    fs.fit(X_train, y_train)
    X_train_fs = fs.transform(X_train)
    X_test_fs = fs.transform(X_test)
    feature_dict ={'variables': features,"importance":fs.scores_}
    feature_df=pd.DataFrame(feature_dict)
    feature_df=feature_df.sort_values(by ='importance', ascending = False).reset_index(drop=True)
    
    # plot the feature importance 
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (20.0, 8.0)
    ## only plot the first 20 variables
    plt.bar(feature_df.iloc[:20,:]['variables'], feature_df.iloc[:20,:]['importance']) 
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right',fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel("Variables",fontsize=20,weight="bold")
    plt.ylabel("Feature importance",fontsize=20,weight="bold")
    plt.title('Feature Importance Plot',fontsize=20,weight="bold")
    plt.show()
    return feature_df

6.4 | Figure 14 | Feature importance Graph¶

The results shows that households that are most likely to be in fuel poverty has the following characteristics: income deciles, in privated rented places, without 'central heating' or 'Storage heater' system, using electricity as main fuel, and having a low EPC rating. These results align well with the results in Section 4. Therefore, when conducting surveys for fuel poverty or social equity study, the above-mentioned factors have the highest priority.

7. Conclusion and Limitations¶

Conclusion
This study carried out classification of the UK fuel poverty dataset in 2015 using 5 poluar classification algorithms,with the aim of answering the following questions:

Q1. Which classification method have the best performance for fuel poverty prediction?

Q2. Which fatcors are most related to fuel poverty?

Q1: Randomforest classifier peroforms better with upsampling technique while other classifiers also show good performance.

RQ2: Income deciles, tenure type, main fuel type, whether have boiler or not, type of central heating system, EPC rating are most related to fuel poverty classification while region, floor area, dwelling age are not prominent to fuel poverty.

The implication of this is that when household income and energy cost information are available, the above-mentioned fators in RQ2 can be collected to preidct fuel poverty and to be used for social/energy equity research.

Limitations and fuel poverty
No hyperparameter tuning was applied to the classifiers. It would be interesting to explore the fuel poverty datasets of last year and this year because of the reduction of income and the soaring fuel price and high inflation rate would drive many more household into fuel poverty. Under current curcumstances, it would be necessary to increase the energy efficiency of the dwelling or buy domestic solar PV panels.
